<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: Just some minor flavour things to make the monster list more Tolkienien...  
    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
 (Novice)Priests/Patriarchs could become Eru or Manwe (High) Priests...  
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 (Novice)Paladins, Knights Templar could become (High) Tulkas Priests 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 In a similar vein, cultists and cult-leaders could become Melkor/Dark Priests.  
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Although it's more of a stretch, Black/Hell Knights could become Knight of Melkor / Knight of Udun.  
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Druids could become Yavannah Priests.  
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Werebears could become Beornings 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Mimics could become Skin-Changers (which, as I recall, is how Gandalf described Beorn to Bilbo) 
</p>
</li>
    <li>
<p>
 Swamp Thing could become Symbiant 
</p>
</li>

    </ul>


<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: I agree on the Beornings, but I don't see how Priests of any kind are really more in theme. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: Worshipper, then? If it's a char-class then maybe should it be considered "ToME in-theme". Understand what you're saying, though.  
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: I like the concept of Werebears --&gt; Beornings. Could they potentially be coaligned, if one's character is of appropriate race and/or class?  
</p>
<p>
Re: all the assorted priests, I'm not clear on whether they are suggested to being renamed or re-worked (I presume renamed.) I do think critters like Knights Templar could go away or be renamed. AFAIK (and feel free to prove me wrong) there's no such thing as a Knight Templar in Tolkien-dom. (Then again, neither is there a yeek....) 
</p>
<p>
Just a few thoughts. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: Yup. Just renamed. Priests (either good or bad) and Paladins don't really have a huge Tolkienian lineage. I had thought dropping them for 2.3 would be a bit of a big prune of the monster list, so I thought renaming them might be a shorter step.  
</p>
